RSYNC VS SCP USE CASE


Here is a line-by-line comparison of rsync vs scp â€” great for interviews and real-time usage:

âœ… 1. Basic Purpose
rsync: Used to synchronize files/directories between local and remote systems.

scp: Used to copy files/directories between local and remote systems.

âœ… 2. Data Transfer Behavior
rsync: Transfers only changed parts of files (delta algorithm).

scp: Transfers the entire file every time.

âœ… 3. Speed & Efficiency
rsync: Faster â€” because it skips identical files or parts.

scp: Slower â€” always sends the whole file.

âœ… 4. Resume Support
rsync: âœ… Yes â€“ supports resume using --partial.

scp: âŒ No â€“ does not support resume; restarts file transfer.

âœ… 5. SSH Support
rsync: âœ… Yes â€“ use with -e ssh.

scp: âœ… Yes â€“ uses SSH by default.

âœ… 6. Compression
rsync: âœ… Use -z for compression.

scp: âœ… Use -C (if supported) for compression.

âœ… 7. Recursive Copy
rsync: âœ… Use -r or -a for recursive sync.

scp: âœ… Use -r for recursive copy.

âœ… 8. Preserve File Permissions
rsync: âœ… Use -a or -p to preserve ownership and timestamps.

scp: âœ… Use -p to preserve timestamps.

âœ… 9. Dry Run (Preview)
rsync: âœ… Use --dry-run to preview sync.

scp: âŒ Not supported.

âœ… 10. Bidirectional Sync
rsync: âœ… Can be configured for two-way sync (with scripts/tools).

scp: âŒ One-way only (copy source â†’ destination).

